"'''Boris, you are wrong'''" ({{lang-ru|Борис, ты не прав}}) is a political [[catchphrase]], originally said by [[Yegor Ligachev]] to [[Boris Yeltsin]] on 1 July 1988 to tackle Yeltsin's split from Soviet politics. Ligachev was at the time a member of the [[Politburo]], while Yeltsin was First Deputy Chairman of the Soviet [[State Committee for Construction]]. Speaking at the 19th All-Union Conference of the [[CPSU]], Ligachev said: "Dear comrades! We should not be silent because communist Yeltsin has chosen a wrong path. It turned out that the man does not have a creative, but a destructive force. His assessment of the ''[[perestroyka]]'' process, the approach and the method of work have been declared untenable and erroneous in the party. There are reasonable proposals in his speech, but in general it indicates that you, Boris, have not drawn the correct political conclusions".<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7hY28PXvHaE| title =Video of Yegor Ligachev's speech|language=Russian|publisher =[[YouTube]]| accessdate =20 February 2014}}</ref> The form "Boris, you are wrong" was popularized by [[Gennady Khazanov]].<ref>{{cite web| url =http://pda.mn.ru/opinions/20130701/350508736.html| archive-url =https://archive.is/20140220005412/http://pda.mn.ru/opinions/20130701/350508736.html| dead-url =yes| archive-date =20 February 2014| title =Ощущение цитаты| publisher =''[[Moskovskiye Novosti]]''| language =Russian| accessdate =20 February 2014}}</ref>
The phrase did not appear in the published protocol of the conference, but within days after that event people in Moscow started to wear lapel buttons saying, "Yegor, you are wrong!"<ref>{{cite book | last =O'Clery | first =Conor | title =Moscow, December 25, 1991: The Last Day of the Soviet Union| publisher =PublicAffairs | year =2011 | page =65 | isbn =1610390121}}</ref> The phrase has been used in later Russian publications to admonish or rebuke the opposing side in the form "''N,'' you are wrong". Following Yeltsin's death in 2007, Ligachev upheld his criticism by saying that what he told Yeltsin back then was right in his opinion.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://politsovet.ru/18209-.html| title =Егор Лигачев: Говоря: "Борис, ты не прав!", я не ошибся |publisher =Politsovet.ru|language=Russian| accessdate =20 February 2014}}</ref> Ligachev's own 2012 memoir book is titled ''Boris Was Wrong'' ({{ISBN|978-5-4438-0089-9}}).
